<% provide(:title, 'JSON Encoding Error Demo') %>
<h1>JSON Encoding Error Demo</h1>

<p class="lead">
  Demonstrates how Ruby DI handles probes that capture binary data.
</p>

<div class="panel panel-info">
  <div class="panel-heading"><h4 class="panel-title">How to Test</h4></div>
  <div class="panel-body">
    <ol>
      <li>In Datadog, set a <strong>method probe</strong> on <code>BinaryDataModel#process</code></li>
      <li>Wait for the probe to appear as active on <%= link_to "DI Probes", probes_path %></li>
      <li>Click <strong>Normal Operation</strong> — snapshot captures and serializes successfully</li>
      <li>Click <strong>Binary data</strong> — binary string passed as method argument, DI serializes it natively without error</li>
      <li>Click <strong>Custom serializer returns binary data</strong> — custom serializer produces a non-UTF-8 binary string, JSON encoding fails, probe is automatically disabled with ERROR status</li>
      <li>Return to <%= link_to "DI Probes", probes_path %> to see the probe status change</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="well">
  <h4>Run the Demo</h4>
  <p class="text-muted" style="margin-bottom: 15px;">
    All three cases use <code>BinaryDataModel#process</code> with a probe on it.
  </p>
  <a href="/debugger_test/binary_data" class="btn btn-success di-demo-btn">
    <strong>Normal Operation</strong><br>
    <small>Snapshot serializes correctly</small>
  </a>
  <a href="/debugger_test/binary_data_param" class="btn btn-success di-demo-btn" style="margin-left: 10px;">
    <strong>Binary data</strong><br>
    <small>Binary string as method argument, DI serializes natively</small>
  </a>
  <a href="/debugger_test/binary_data?trigger_error=true" class="btn btn-danger di-demo-btn" style="margin-left: 10px;">
    <strong>Custom serializer returns binary data</strong><br>
    <small>Probe will be disabled with ERROR status</small>
  </a>

  <div id="di-demo-result" style="display: none; margin-top: 15px;"></div>
</div>

<script>
  document.querySelectorAll('.di-demo-btn').forEach(function(btn) {
    btn.addEventListener('click', function(e) {
      e.preventDefault();
      var url = this.getAttribute('href');
      var label = this.querySelector('strong').textContent;
      var resultEl = document.getElementById('di-demo-result');

      resultEl.style.display = 'none';

      fetch(url)
        .then(function(res) { return res.text(); })
        .then(function(text) {
          resultEl.className = 'alert alert-info';
          resultEl.innerHTML = '<strong>' + label + ':</strong> ' + text;
          resultEl.style.display = 'block';
        })
        .catch(function(err) {
          resultEl.className = 'alert alert-danger';
          resultEl.innerHTML = '<strong>Error:</strong> ' + err;
          resultEl.style.display = 'block';
        });
    });
  });
</script>

<div class="panel panel-default">
  <div class="panel-heading"><h4 class="panel-title">Background</h4></div>
  <div class="panel-body">
    <p>
      When a DI probe fires on a method, it captures a <strong>snapshot</strong> of local variables
      and arguments. That snapshot is serialized to JSON and sent to Datadog.
    </p>
    <p>
      If a custom serializer returns a raw binary string (non-UTF-8), JSON encoding fails.
      Without error handling, this failure is silent: snapshots are dropped, the probe appears
      healthy, and only telemetry tracks the issue.
    </p>
    <p>
      With proper error handling (dd-trace-rb PR #5448), a JSON encoding failure
      <strong>disables the probe and reports ERROR status</strong> to the Datadog UI.
      DI's own serializer handles binary strings safely without this problem.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>
